<!doctype html><html lang="en"><head><meta meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1"><meta name="format-detection" content="telephone=no"><title>Weeksinyear - Calculate Download time/speed</title><meta name="Description" content="Download time calculator helps you to calculate the download time it takes to download a file based on your internet download speed/bandwidth."><meta name="Keywords" content="download,time,calculate, Estimate,bandwidth,broadband,downloadspeed,speed,upload,upload time calculator"><meta property="og:title" content="Download Time Calculator - Calculate Download time" <script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-9052896293064464"
     crossorigin="anonymous"></script><meta property="og:type" content="website"><meta property="og:url" content="http://downloadtimecalculator.com/"><meta property="og:image" content="http://downloadtimecalculator.com/Download-Time-Calculator.png"><link rel="stylesheet" href="calstyles.css?v=4"><!-- google fonts  --><link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com"><link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin><style>.active1{color: white;}</style></head><body><!-- Navbar  --> <?php include('navbar.php') ?> <!-- MAIN BODY  --><div class="text-center mt-5 w3-animate-zoom"><h1>Download Time Calculator</h1><h3><span class="">Calculate Download Time</span></h3><h4><span class="">How long will it take to download?</span></h4></div><div class="desktopcenter ebbg_color"><div class="content"><form onsubmit="return false"><!-- card 1 --><div id="speed" class="p-4 rounded card"><h3>How fast is your internet speed?</h3><h4>Download Speed</h4><p><label for="internetSpeed"></label><input id="internetSpeed_p" type="button" value="+" onclick="internetSpeed.value = (parseInt(internetSpeed.value)+1).toFixed(2)"> <input id="internetSpeed" type="number" min="0" step="0.01" value="10" placeholder="Download speed" autofocus> <input id="internetSpeed_p" type="button" value="-" onclick="internetSpeed.value = (parseInt(internetSpeed.value)-1).toFixed(2)"><select id="internetSpeedBase" aria-label="Unit of speed like Kbps, Mbps, Gbps"><option value="10^3">Kbps</option><option value="10^6" selected="selected">Mbps</option><option value="10^9">Gbps</option></select></p><p class="idkSpeed"><a id="speedtestLink" href="http://speedtest.net" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">I don't know my internet speed</a></p><div><label class="collapse-head" for="_1">?</label><input id="_1" type="checkbox"><div><p class="overhead-p"><label for="internetOverhead">Overhead</label><select style="font-size: 1rem;" id="internetOverhead"><option value="1" selected="selected">None</option><option value="0.99">1%</option><option value="0.95">5%</option><option value="0.9">10% (Typical TCP overhead)</option><option value="0.85">15%</option><option value="0.8">20%</option><option value="0.75">25%</option><option value="0.7">30%</option><option value="0.6">40%</option><option value="0.5">50%</option><option value="0.4">60%</option><option value="0.3">70%</option><option value="0.2">80%</option><option value="0.1">90%</option><option value="0.05">95%</option><option value="0.01">99%</option></select></p></div></div></div><!-- card 2 --><div class="p-4 rounded card" id="file"><h3>What is the size of the thing you want to download?</h3><h4>Download Size</h4><p><label for="fileSize"></label><input id="internetSpeed_p" type="button" value="+" onclick="fileSize.value = (parseInt(fileSize.value)+1).toFixed(2)"> <input type="number" id="fileSize" value="1" step="0.01" min="0"> <input id="internetSpeed_p" type="button" aria-label="Data unit like KB, MB, GB" value="-" onclick="fileSize.value = (parseInt(fileSize.value)-1).toFixed(2)"><select id="fileSizeBase"><option value="2^10">KB</option><option value="2^20">MB</option><option value="2^30" selected="selected">GB</option><option value="2^40">TB</option></select></p><p><button style="margin: 0 auto;" class="cal-button" id="calculateButton">Calculate</button></p></div></form><!-- card 3 result --><div class="p-4 rounded card" id="results" style="background-color: #dce9ff;"><div id="results_inner"><p class="">It would take</p><p style="color:green" class="time">0</p><p class="">to transfer<span class="size"></span></p><p class="">at<span class="speed"></span>/sec</p></div><div class="didyouknow"><a href="./doyouknow" target="_blank">Did you know that there is a HUGE difference between Mbps and MBps?</a></div><hr></div></div></div><div class="info ebbg_color"><!-- card  --><div class="content"><div class="card p-4 rounded" style="background-color: #dce9ff;"><h2>What is Download Time Calculator?</h2><p>Download time calculator is used to estimate the time required to download any file based on your transfer speed without actually downloading any file.</p><h3>How to use?</h3><p>1. Enter your transfer speed.<br>2. Enter the file size of the thing you want to download.<br>3. This tool will estimate the time it would take to download.</p><p></p></div><!-- <img src="Download-Time-Calculator.png" alt="Download Time Calculator" class="downloadtimeimage"> --><div class="card p-4 rounded mt-3" style="background-color: #dce9ff;"><h2>Typical Internet speeds</h2><table class=""><thead><tr><th><h3 class="text-white">Connection type</h3></th><th><h3 class="text-white">Download speed</h3></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>OLD Modem</td><td>28,8 kbit/s<tr><td>DSL Modem</td><td>56,6 kbit/s<tr><td>ADSL</td><td>512 kbit/s<tr><td>ADSL</td><td>1 Mbit/s<tr><td>ADSL</td><td>8 Mbit/s<tr><td>ADSL</td><td>24 Mbit/s<tr><td>LAN</td><td>10 Mbit/s<tr><td>3G</td><td>7.2 Mbit/s<tr><td>4G</td><td>80 Mbit/s<tr><td>LAN</td><td>100 Mbit/s<tr><td>Fiber obtic</td><td>1000 Mbit/s</td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></tbody></table></div><!-- card  --><div class="card p-3 rounded mt-2"><h2>Typical download sizes</h2><div><table><thead><tr><th><p class="text-white">Connection type</p></th><th><p class="text-white">Download speed</p></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Text email</td><td>30 kB<tr><td>A webpage</td><td>600 kB<tr><td>Photo</td><td>1 MB<tr><td>Mp3 song</td><td>5 MB<tr><td>5 min Youtube 360p video</td><td>40 MB<tr><td>A SD movie</td><td>750 MB<tr><td>A HD Movie</td><td>4 GB</td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div><!-- card  --><div class="card p-4 rounded m-2 text-center"><h2>Difference between MBps and Mbps</h2><p class="bol">All internet service provider use the term Mbps to mention their speed, while most applications show MBps/KBps to indicate the download speed. People often get confused in between MB(Mega BYTE) and Mb(Mega bit) and ISPs take advantage of this fact by mentioning all the speeds in Mbps.<br></p><p class="bol">1MBps = 8Mbps<br>1MB = 8Mb<br>1KB = 8Kb</p></div><!-- card  --><div class="card p-4 rounded m-2 text-center"><h2>Theoretical speed</h2><p class="bol">The speeds shown by download time calculator is purely theoretical. We try to simulate the real world scenario as much as possible, but It is not always possible to have the same speed over a continuous period of time. Your download speed will depend on various other factors like the upload speed of the web-server, distance between your computer and the server and other disturbences.<br>The quality of your internet connection is also dependent on<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_latency_and_throughput" target="_blank">latency</a>and<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jitter" target="_blank">jitter</a>(noise). It is possible to have high throughput(speed) but low quality.</p></div><!-- card  --><div class="card p-4 rounded m-2 text-center"><h2>How to increase download speed</h2><p class="bol">Increasing download speed is a common concern for many internet users, especially those with high-speed broadband connections. Slow download speeds can be frustrating, but there are several ways to improve the rate at which files, games, and software download onto your device. One effective solution is to install a reliable download manager, such as<a href="http://internetdownloadmanager.com/getlatestversion.html?ai=200272979" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">"Internet Download Manager"</a>(IDM), which can significantly enhance your download experience.<br>Download managers like IDM can be instrumental in boosting download speeds by employing various techniques. These programs often create multiple simultaneous connections to the server from which you're downloading the file. This approach divides the file into smaller, manageable chunks, which are downloaded concurrently. As a result, your overall download speed increases because you're effectively utilizing your available bandwidth more efficiently.<br>To maximize your download speed using a download manager like IDM, follow these steps:<br></p><p class="text-left"><b>1) Download and Install IDM:</b>Start by downloading and installing Internet Download Manager on your computer. You can usually find it on the official IDM website or authorized software download platforms.<br><b>2) Integrate with Your Browser:</b>IDM can integrate seamlessly with popular web browsers like Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Microsoft Edge, and others. During installation, it usually prompts you to add its extension or plugin to your browser, making it easy to initiate downloads directly through IDM.<br><b>3) Configure IDM Settings:</b>Once installed, open IDM and configure its settings to suit your preferences. You can adjust parameters such as the number of concurrent connections, download speed limits, and download locations. Optimizing these settings can help tailor IDM to your specific needs.<br><b>4) Start Downloads:</b>When you initiate a download through your browser, IDM will take over and manage the download process. It will create multiple connections to the server, enabling faster download speeds.<br><b>5) Monitor Progress:</b>IDM provides a user-friendly interface that allows you to monitor the progress of your downloads. You can pause, resume, or prioritize downloads as needed.<br><b>6) Schedule Downloads:</b>IDM also offers a scheduling feature, allowing you to set specific times for downloads. This is particularly useful if you want to take advantage of off-peak hours for faster download speeds.<br><b>7) Automatic Capture:</b>IDM can automatically capture download links from webpages, making it convenient to initiate downloads without manually copying and pasting URLs.<br><b>8) Use Mirror Links:</b>Some websites offer mirror links for downloads. IDM can automatically detect and use these mirror links if available, potentially increasing download speed.<br></p><p class="bol">By following these steps and utilizing a download manager like IDM, you can significantly enhance your download speed and enjoy faster access to files, games, and software. Remember that your actual download speed may also be influenced by factors such as the server's capacity, your internet service provider's network congestion, and the health of your network equipment, so it's essential to ensure these components are in good condition for optimal performance.</p></div></div></div><div><!-- footer  --> <?php include('footer.php'); ?> <!-- footer end  --></div><script src="script.js"></script></body></html>